---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SectionHeading from '../components/SectionHeading.astro';

const title = 'About';
const description =
  'Komon Lab is a one-person project that makes free, printable kimono patterns from your measurements. No VC, no growth hacks, no email lists.';
const contactEmail = import.meta.env.PUBLIC_CONTACT_EMAIL;
const contactHandle = import.meta.env.PUBLIC_CONTACT_HANDLE;
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  path="/about"
  breadcrumbs={[
    { name: 'Home', path: '/' },
    { name: 'About', path: '/about' },
  ]}
>
  <section class="py-16">
    <div class="container-readable">
      <SectionHeading
        eyebrow="About the project"
        title="A small workshop in public."
      />

      <div class="prose-komon mt-10">
        <h2>What this is</h2>
        <p>
          Komon Lab is a single tool with a few guides around it. The tool turns seven body
          measurements into a printable kimono pattern. The guides explain the assumptions inside
          the tool — how to measure, what the fabric widths mean, which sewing tools are actually
          worth owning — so you can disagree with the tool when it’s wrong.
        </p>

        <h2>Why it exists</h2>
        <p>
          The English-language kimono sewing internet has a strange shape. There are excellent
          Japanese-language books, a few translated patterns, and a long tail of forum threads.
          What there isn’t much of is a tool that takes <em>your</em> measurements and gives back
          a pattern. Everything is graded from one fictional standard body, with two or three
          alternative sizes on a good day.
        </p>
        <p>
          That mismatch makes kimono sewing feel inaccessible to people whose proportions don’t fit
          the chart, or who can only source 110 cm fabric. Komon Lab is a small attempt to fix
          that — by treating the proportional rules of traditional <em>wasai</em> as a generator,
          not a frozen size grid.
        </p>

        <h2>Who built it</h2>
        <p>
          One person, working in the evenings. Not a heritage tailor, not a credentialed sewing
          instructor — a sewer who got frustrated and started writing code. The maths in the tool
          is documented in the source so anyone with sewing experience can read it, disagree, and
          send corrections.
        </p>

        <h2>How it stays free</h2>
        <p>
          The site is statically built and hosted on Cloudflare Pages, which is free at this scale.
          The pattern PDFs are generated in your browser, which means I don’t pay for compute when
          you make one. Analytics is Umami, which is cookieless and counts pageviews without
          identifying you.
        </p>
        <p>
          If the bills ever grow, the plan is small affiliate links on the guides — labelled, for
          things I’d already recommend — before anything else. No paywall, no email list, no
          “premium PDFs.”
        </p>

        <h2>How to help</h2>
        <p>
          Sew a kimono from the tool and tell me what failed. Photos of the fit issue help more
          than words. If you can read Japanese sewing books and spot somewhere I’ve simplified the
          maths in a way that breaks tradition, I want to hear about it.
        </p>

        <h2>Contact</h2>
        {contactEmail || contactHandle ? (
          <p>
            {contactEmail && (
              <>Email: <a href={`mailto:${contactEmail}`}>{contactEmail}</a></>
            )}
            {contactEmail && contactHandle && <span> · </span>}
            {contactHandle && (
              <>Social: <code>{contactHandle}</code></>
            )}
          </p>
        ) : (
          <p>
            A public contact channel is being decided. In the meantime, please hold onto your
            feedback — it will be wanted as soon as one is open.
          </p>
        )}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
